messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full path: /printdocument/{id}/budget

- All HTTP methods acceptable: false

- HEAD acceptable: false

- POST acceptable: true

- OPTIONS acceptable: false

- TRACE acceptable: false

- GET acceptable: false

- PUT acceptable: false

- DELETE acceptable: false

- PATCH acceptable: false

Explanation:
- The handler method is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/printdocument/{id}/budget", method = RequestMethod.POST). There is no class-level @RequestMapping, so the full path is exactly /printdocument/{id}/budget and the method explicitly accepts only POST.
- Because the code explicitly restricts the mapping to RequestMethod.POST, no other HTTP methods are declared as acceptable in the source. Per your instruction to base acceptability on the code (not on framework runtime behavior), only POST is marked acceptable.
- The path parameter is {id} as declared in the annotation and bound in the method via @PathVariable("id") long id. The method is also @Secured("ROLE_USER"), i.e. requires the ROLE_USER authority, though that does not change the HTTP-method mapping.
